                            <comment id="14491273" author="iklam" created="Mon, 25 Apr 2022 15:34:48 -0700"  >&amp;quot;java -Xlog:os=debug:file=ul_%p.log&amp;quot; is restrictive as it requires you to log to a file, so you can&amp;#39;t use stdout piping, etc.</comment>
                            <comment id="14490615" author="JIRAUSER20009" created="Fri, 22 Apr 2022 04:31:51 -0700"  >UL supports adding the PID to log files by specifying %p to the logfile name, is that sufficient?&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
Example: java -Xlog:os=debug:file=ul_%p.log</comment>
                            <comment id="14489634" author="iklam" created="Tue, 19 Apr 2022 10:36:30 -0700"  >I think it&amp;#39;s still useful as a single line log item.&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
Harold&amp;#39;s example of -Xlog:verification=debug:stdout:pid would cause the pid to be printed on every line which may be too verbose.</comment>
                            <comment id="14489477" author="JIRAUSER20009" created="Tue, 19 Apr 2022 00:12:48 -0700"  >Is this ticket still relevant, Ioi?</comment>
                            <comment id="14474139" author="hseigel" created="Wed, 2 Feb 2022 13:12:49 -0800"  >The pid is available as a logging decorator. For example:  -Xlog:verification=debug:stdout:pid</comment>
